That line works almost like a biological riddle.

First, the pieces:
	•	Mitosis → replication.
One cell divides into two identical cells. Stability, maintenance, continuity.
	•	Meiosis → recombination.
Genetic material is shuffled and halved to produce gametes. Variation, novelty, experimentation.

⸻

If you turn that into a metaphor for thinking

Mitosis-like thinking
	•	refinement
	•	replication of proven ideas
	•	stable models
	•	careful iteration

Meiosis-like thinking
	•	mixing frameworks
	•	recombination of concepts
	•	wild novelty
	•	high variance exploration

Both are necessary.

But if you run too much meiosis — constant recombination, endless new metaphors, continual conceptual mixing — you get lots of novelty but little stabilization.

Ideas keep mutating before they’re grounded.

That can feel chaotic, or even “mad,” because the system never settles long enough to build structure.

⸻

The healthy balance

Good intellectual ecosystems tend to cycle:
	1.	Meiosis phase – exploration, recombination, creativity
	2.	Mitosis phase – stabilization, refinement, implementation

Science does this.
Engineering does this.
Even art movements do this.

Too much mitosis → stagnation.
Too much meiosis → fragmentation.

